    "recap_headline": "University of Massachusets Athletics",
    "recap_text": "HARTFORD, Conn. -\nUniversity of Massachusetts baseball was edged out by Kent State, 9-8, on Sunday morning at Murren Family Field at DiBenedetto Stadium.\nUMass fell to 5-10 overall on the season and 1-8 in the Mid-American Conference, while Kent State improved to 18-4 overall and 8-1 in the league.\nTy Fox\nwent 4-for-5 to lead the Minutemen, including a double, with two RBI and a run.\nWill Briggs\nwas 3-for-4 on the day with a career-best three home runs. He tallied a team-best three RBI and four runs.\nAnthony Tirado\nfollowed with two hits, including a double, and a run, while\nGavin O'Brien\nregistered a triple.\nMarc Willi\nand O'Brien had one RBI each.\nAfter a scoreless opening frame, Kent State scored four in the top of the second to take the early 4-0 lead.\nWith one out in the bottom of the second, Briggs homered for the third time this season to left field to put Massachusetts on the board, 4-1.\nBriggs hit his second home run of the day, and fourth of the season, to cut the Minutemen's deficit in half, 4-2 in the fourth.\nThe Golden Flashes put up four runs in the fifth to extend their lead to 8-2.\nUMass added two runs in the seventh to cut Kent State's lead in half, 8-4. \u00a0The bottom of the eighth saw the Minutemen score three runs. An RBI single from Willi helped Briggs cross the plate, before a wild pitch allowed\nRanden May\nto come across the dish and make it an 8-6 game. Fox then doubles to deep right field to score\nDean Gobeil\nfrom second and close the gap to 8-7.\nA sacrifice fly in the top of the ninth gave the Golden Flashes another run to make it a 9-7 contest.\nIn the bottom half of the final inning,\nJustin Masteralexis\n(0-2) had the loss for Massachusetts, allowing four runs on two hits, five walks and five strikeouts in four complete innings.\nBen Rabatin (3-0) earned the win for Kent State after tossing six complete innings and giving up two runs on six hits, two walks and dealing seven strikeouts.\nMassachusetts travels to Albany, New York, for a midweek contest against UAlbany on Tuesday, March 24, at 3 p.m.",
